dot("$C$", C, NW);

dot("$A'$", Ap, E);
dot("$B'$", Bp, SW);
dot("$C'$", Cp, SW);
[/asy]

We then rotate the diagram $90^\circ$ counter-clockwise around the origin:

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, B, C, App, Bpp, Cpp;

A = (0,2);
B = (-3,2);
C = (-3,0);
App = rotate(90)*reflect((0,0),(1,0))*(A);
Bpp = rotate(90)*reflect((0,0),(1,0))*(B);
Cpp = rotate(90)*reflect((0,0),(1,0))*(C);

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(App--Bpp--Cpp--cycle);
draw((-3.5,0)--(3.5,0));
draw((0,-3.5)--(0,3.5));

dot("$A$", A, E);
dot("$B$", B, NW);
dot("$C$", C, S);

dot("$A''$", App, N);
dot("$B''$", Bpp, SE);
dot("$C''$", Cpp, W);
[/asy]

Then to transform triangle $A''B''C''$ to triangle $ABC,$ we can reflect over the line $y = x.$  The answer is $\boxed{\text{(D)}}.$

